  title: "The Waste Hierarchy: Recycling is Your Last Resort, Not the First",
  date: "October 8, 2025",
  image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1532996122724-e3c354a0b15b?q=80&w=2070&auto=format&fit=crop",
  excerpt: "The most powerful thing you can do for the planet is prevent waste from being created in the first place. Think of the 5 R's as a checklist where the top items are the most important.",
  content: ["ðŸ¥‡ Rank 1: Refuse & Reduce", "Say 'No' to single-use plastics and packaging. Buy less stuff overall. This saves the most energy, water, and raw materials because you avoid manufacturing entirely.", "Why It Matters: This is the most impactful action you can take. When you refuse unnecessary items and reduce your consumption, you prevent waste at its source. No manufacturing means no energy consumption, no water usage, no raw material extraction, and no transportation emissions.", "ðŸ¥ˆ Rank 2: Reuse & Repurpose", "Fix, donate, or find a new creative use for an item before you toss it. This extends the product's life and delays its trip to the landfill or recycling plant.", "Why It Matters: Every time you reuse an item, you're getting more value from the resources that went into making it. Repairing instead of replacing, donating instead of discarding, and repurposing items creatively keeps materials in use longer and reduces demand for new products.", "ðŸ¥‰ Rank 3: Recycle", "Only after all other options have failed, place items (clean and sorted!) into the correct bin. Recycling still requires significant energy. It's the best end-of-life option, but not the best first choice.", "Why It Matters: While recycling is better than landfilling, it still consumes energy and resources to collect, sort, clean, and reprocess materials. Contaminated recyclables can ruin entire batches. Recycling should be your last resort after you've exhausted all options to refuse, reduce, and reuse."]
