  title: "Food Waste: A Methane Monster in the Landfill",
  date: "October 6, 2025",
  image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1542601906990-b4d3fb778b09?q=80&w=2013&auto=format&fit=crop",
  excerpt: "When you throw away food, you're not just wasting money; you're fueling climate change.",
  content: ["Methane is the Problem", "When food rots in a landfill (without oxygen), it releases methane (CHâ‚„). Methane is a greenhouse gas 80 times more potent than carbon dioxide in the short term. This means that every piece of food waste in a landfill is actively contributing to global warming at an accelerated rate.", "The anaerobic decomposition process in landfills creates the perfect environment for methane production. Without oxygen, organic matter breaks down differently than it would in nature, producing this powerful greenhouse gas that traps heat in our atmosphere much more effectively than COâ‚‚.", "Waste of Resources", "Wasted food means wasted land, wasted water, and wasted energy used to grow, transport, and cook it. Every apple thrown away represents gallons of water used for irrigation, acres of farmland, fuel for transportation, and energy for refrigeration and cooking.", "Consider the full lifecycle: farmers worked the land, used pesticides and fertilizers, harvested the crops, trucked them to distribution centers, stored them in refrigerated warehouses, delivered them to stores, and you brought them home. All of that effort and resource consumption is wasted when food ends up in the trash.", "The Simple Solution: Compost", "The best final destination for food scraps (peels, cores, coffee grounds) is composting. Composting uses oxygen, which converts the waste into beneficial soil nutrients instead of climate-warming methane.", "When you compost, you're completing nature's cycle. Organic matter breaks down aerobically (with oxygen) to create nutrient-rich soil amendment that helps plants grow, retains moisture, and sequesters carbon. This transforms a climate problem into a climate solution while reducing the need for chemical fertilizers."]
